{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":19867,"record_hash":"sha256:0656808de3dc3e0699ff134da50933ac75012ce057034dab4c79f827c5a4a909","timestamp":"2026-05-10T10:58:18.430Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Mostly because `set_record()` needs a serde-serializable “record shape” whose field names become GitMeta key suffixes.\n\nWe *could* try to use `SessionUpdate`, but it mixes several things:\n\n- operational inputs: `target`, `records`\n- identity/routing: `session_key`, `source_key`\n- source metadata: `agent`, `provider`, `model`, `tool_version`\n- session metadata: `schema`, `updated_at`, which `SessionUpdate` does not actually contain\n\nSo serializing `SessionUpdate` directly would require lots of `#[serde(skip)]`, custom redaction handling, and probably still would not map cleanly because session fields and source fields are written under different prefixes.\n\n`SessionMetadata` and `SourceMetadata` are basically tiny persistence views:\n\n```rust\nhandle.set_record(session_prefix, SessionMetadata { ... })?;\nhandle.set_record(source_prefix, self.source_metadata())?;\n```\n\nThey exist so the storage shape is attached to Rust fields instead of loose string keys like:\n\n```rust\nhandle.set(&key(prefix, \"updated-at\"), ...)?;\nhandle.set(&key(source_prefix, \"tool-version\"), ...)?;\n```\n\nThat said, your instinct is fair: these should not become “domain types.” They are just serialization adapters. If the names feel too grand, I’d rename them to make that clearer, maybe:\n\n```rust\nStoredSessionFields\nStoredSourceFields\n```\n\nor even:\n\n```rust\nSessionFields\nSourceFields\n```\n\nI would not use the existing `SessionUpdate` type for this. It would make the code more fragile, not simpler.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-10T10:58:18.430Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final